FLRC-F: Financial Prediction Variant

Core Principle

Financial prediction uses past market dynamics to construct candidate profitable future states, then searches backward for feasible paths from present conditions to those states.

Instead of predicting a price directly, advanced systems effectively ask:

What market conditions would produce a profitable outcome, and how close is the current system state to that path?

⸻

Structural Model for Markets

Define:
	•	Mₚ = past market states
	•	M₀ = current market state
	•	M_f = profitable future state
	•	T(x) = market transition dynamics
	•	R(P) = risk-adjusted cost of path

⸻

Stage 1 — Pattern Extraction

From price history, volume, and macro signals:

M_p \rightarrow T(x)

The system learns transition tendencies such as:
	•	momentum
	•	mean reversion
	•	volatility clustering
	•	liquidity flows

⸻

Stage 2 — Future Profit States

Instead of “predict price,” systems define profit conditions:

Examples:

price breakout
volatility expansion
liquidity imbalance
mean reversion snap

These become candidate future states M_f.

⸻

Stage 3 — Reverse Construction

The algorithm asks:

What path from current conditions could plausibly reach that state?

Search:

M_f \rightarrow M_0

This reveals necessary precursor patterns.

Examples:
	•	accumulation phases
	•	volatility compression
	•	trend initiation

⸻

Stage 4 — Minimum Risk Path

Among possible strategies, choose the one minimizing:

risk
capital exposure
drawdown probability
time to payoff

Formally:

P^* = \arg\min R(P)

